{"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"LINK","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"href":"https://www.youtube.com/@LucidRhythms"}},"1":{"type":"LINK","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyrhythm"}}},"blocks":[{"key":"85rmm","text":"I was perusing YouTube, as one does, and encountered a fascinating channel called Lucid Rhythms. Highly recommend! Through the process of watching their videos, I began to dissect them and attempt to figure out how they work.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"offset":80,"length":13,"key":0}],"data":{}},{"key":"6rce2","text":"Polyrhythm is the simultaneous use of two or more rhythms that are not readily perceived as deriving from one another, or as simple manifestations of the same meter.","type":"blockquote","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"wikicite","text":"Wikipedia.org","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"offset":0,"length":13,"key":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"3onbd","text":"To accomplish this, I used some math to set the velocity of each ball to be a ratio of the other ball velocities. There is a simple mathematical function that sets the velocity. Each ball is assigned a specific tone on the repeating scale of A, C, E, G in different octaves. When the ball touches a wall, the assigned tone plays.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}]}
